<section xml:id="sec-roots-fractions-prep" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
  <title>Roots and Fractional Powers Prep Activities</title>

  <investigation xml:id="pa-ceo-pay">
    <introduction>
        <p>
            Roberts' Law for CEO Compensation<fn>cf. Gabaix, Xavier. <q>Power Laws in Economics and Finance.</q> Annu. Rev. Econ. 2009. 1:255 - 93. doi: 10.1146/annurev.economics.050708.142940</fn> says that at a given moment in time, CEO compensation for large companies is proportional to the 1/3rd power of their size. Total revenue is one way to measure a company's size.
            <!-- Firm size is often measured as <term>market capitalization</term>, which is the total value of all shares currently owned by stockholders. -->
        </p>
        <!-- <p>
            Let <m>C</m> be CEO compensation, in millions of dollars, and <m>S</m> be firm size, measured as market capitalization in billions of dollars. Suppose the table below shows the CEO compensation and market capitalization for several companies.
        </p> -->
        <p>
            Let <m>C</m> be CEO compensation, in millions of dollars, and <m>S</m> be company size size, measured by revenue in billions of dollars. Suppose the table below shows the CEO compensation and market capitalization for several companies.
        </p>
        <table>
            <title>CEO Compensation vs. Revenue (Company Size)</title>
            <tabular  halign="center" top="minor" bottom = "minor" right="minor" left="minor">
                <row header="yes">
                    <cell><m>S</m></cell>
                    <cell><m>C</m></cell>
                </row>
                <row>
                    <cell>15</cell>
                    <cell>13.1</cell>
                </row>
                <row>
                    <cell>25</cell>
                    <cell>15.5</cell>
                </row>
                <row>
                    <cell>45</cell>
                    <cell>18.9</cell>
                </row>
                <row>
                    <cell>75</cell>
                    <cell>22.4</cell>
                </row>
                <row>
                    <cell>105</cell>
                    <cell>25.0</cell>
                </row>
            </tabular>
        </table>
    </introduction>
    <task>
        <statement>
            <p>
                Translate the sentence about Roberts' Law into a power model equation.
            </p>
        </statement>
    </task>
    <task>
        <statement>
            <p>
                Use the data to estimate the constant or proportionality
            </p>
        </statement>
    </task>
    <task>
        <statement>
            <p>
                Pepsi's total revenue in 2024 was about $91 billion, and they reported a total CEO compensation package of about $25 million in reports filed to the SEC. How well does your model predict Pepsi's CEO's compensation package from Pepsi's revenue?
            </p>
        </statement>
    </task>
  </investigation>

  <investigation xml:id="pa-defining-roots">
    <introduction>
        <p>
            We learned how to use roots to help us solve equations in <xref ref="pa-using-roots-to-solve"/>. If we want to solve an equation like
            <me>343 = x^3</me>, then we take the cube root of both sides <me>\sqrt[3]{343} = \sqrt[3]{x^3}</me> and get <me>7 = x</me>.
        </p>
        <p>
            What do roots really mean? Let's explore. 
        </p>
    </introduction>
    <task>
        <statement>
            <p>
                Square root of <m>x</m> (<m>\sqrt{x}</m>, or <m>\sqrt[2]{x}</m>) is the positive number that multiplies by itself to get <m>x</m>. That is, 
                <me>\sqrt{x} \cdot \sqrt{x} = x</me>. For example, <m>\sqrt{9} = 3</m> because <m>3 \times 3 = 9</m>.
            </p>
            <p>
                Use this idea to find <m>\sqrt{16}</m>, <m>\sqrt{64}</m>, and <m>\sqrt{1}</m> without using a calculator.
            </p>
        </statement>
    </task>
    <task>
        <statement>
            <p>
                Can you find <m>\sqrt{0}</m>? What about <m>\sqrt{-9}</m>?
            </p>
        </statement>
    </task>
    <task>
        <statement>
            <p>
                Cube root of <m>x</m> (<m>\sqrt[3]{x}</m>) is the number that gives <m>x</m> when you multiply it by itself three times. That is,
                <me>\sqrt[3]{x} \cdot \sqrt[3]{x} \cdot\sqrt[3]{x} = x</me>. For example, <m>\sqrt{27} = 3</m> because <m>3 \times 3 \times 3 = 27</m>.
            </p>
            <p>
                Use this idea to find <m>\sqrt[3]{8}</m> and <m>\sqrt[3]{125}</m> without using a calculator.
            </p>
        </statement>
    </task>
    <task>
        <statement>
            <p>
                Can you find <m>\sqrt[3]{0}</m>? What about <m>\sqrt[3]{-1}</m>?
            </p>
        </statement>
    </task>
    <task>
        <statement>
            <p>
                Test your understanding by extending this idea to a new root! Write a sentence and an equation explaining what the fourth root of <m>x</m> (<m>\sqrt[4]{x}</m>) means, and use your idea to find <m>\sqrt[4]{81}</m> without using a calculator.
            </p>
        </statement>
    </task>
  </investigation>

